  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="KT220-kilavi">paruva varaviṉkaṇ kiḻatti tōḻikku uraittatu </p>
        <p xml:lang="en">SHE talking to the confidante at the coming of the
          season. </p>
      </div>

      <div rend="parallel">
        <lg xml:id="KT220">

          <l>paḻamaḻaik kalitta putuppuṉa varaki</l>
          <l>ṉiralai mēynta kuṟaittalaip pāvai</l>
          <l>yiruvicēr maruṅkiṟ pūtta mullai</l>
          <l>verukucirit taṉṉa pacuvī meṉpiṇik</l>
          <l>kuṟumukai yaviḻnta naṟumalarp puṟaviṉ</l>
          <l>vaṇṭucūḻ mālaiyum vārār</l>
          <l>kaṇṭiciṟ ṟōḻi poruṭpirin tōrē.</l>
        </lg>

        <lg xml:lang="en">

          <l>He has not come even in the evening, when the bees gather</l>
          <l rend="indent3">in the woodland of fragrant blossoms, the little buds opening</l>
          <l rend="indent2">[their] tender fetters into fresh blooms, like the laugh of the wild
            cat,</l>
          <l rend="indent4">on the jasmine, flowering beside <note place="foot">The relation of <term xml:lang="ta">cēr</term> is unmarked; it might also go together with <term xml:lang="ta">iruvi</term> , i.e. "stubbles joining" = all the stubbles.</note> the
            stubble</l>
          <l rend="indent5">– an image <note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">pāvai</term> is
            explained here by T.V.G. to be a quasi-synonym of <term xml:lang="ta">iruvi </term>
            (with parallels in AN 23.7f., 136.11-13). It also seems possible to understand it in the
            usual meaning, though the impact is slightly unclear.</note> of missing heads, <note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">kuṟai talai pāvai</term> : the meaning of this phrase
            is mysterious, since the relations are once more totally unmarked. It might be an
            attribute to <term xml:lang="ta">iruvi</term> : the stubble has been bereft of ears by
            the grazing animals, and thus is, so to speak, lacking heads.</note> grazed by the Iralai –</l>
          <l rend="indent5">of the millet on the new field, swollen in the old rain, <note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">paḻa maḻai</term> might refer to the topos of the
            mistaken rainy season, only that the rest of the poem seems to describe the rainy season
            proper. What other reason is there to term the rain old?</note> </l>
          <l rend="indent2">− look, friend, he who has separated because of wealth.</l>

        </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
